{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652094"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18511"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11240"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7468"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe metatarsal bones are important weight-bearing structures in the foot that form part of the longitudinal and transverse arches.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first metatarsal bone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thinnest metatarsal shaft","Shortest and thickest metatarsal","Most commonly fractured metatarsal","Most laterally positioned metatarsal","Longest metatarsal in the foot"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eshortest and thickest metatarsal\u003C/strong\u003E (image) accurately describes the first metatarsal bone. This robust structure is adapted for its role in weight-bearing and push-off during gait.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThinnest metatarsal shaft\u003C/strong\u003E - The lateral metatarsals (particularly the fifth) tend to have thinner shafts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost commonly fractured metatarsal\u003C/strong\u003E - The fifth metatarsal is most commonly fractured, particularly at its base (Jones fracture) and occurs due to a stress or direct trauma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost laterally positioned metatarsal\u003C/strong\u003E - The fifth metatarsal is the most lateral bone in the series\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELongest metatarsal in the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - The second metatarsal is typically the longest\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first metatarsal is crucial in supporting the medial longitudinal arch and bears significant weight during standing and walking. Its thick, robust structure reflects these essential biomechanical functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The metatarsal bones are numbered 1-5 from medial to lateral in the foot.","The first metatarsal is the shortest and thickest of the metatarsals.","Each metatarsal has a base proximally, shaft (diaphysis), and head distally."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cFirst Metatarsal Bone\u201d by DBCLS is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 2.1 jp Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.1/jp/deed.en). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:First_metatarsal_bone04.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21388"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21388"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Ecdb1ZxUbAJVCxgEYGByNpdWBExGMc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Ecdb1ZxUbAJVCxgEYGByNpdWBExGMc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T21:50:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T21:50:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11240"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":